# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qos-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] As related to network technology, COS is a 3-bit field that is present in an Ethernet frame header when 802.1Q VLAN tagging is present.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] The field specifies a priority value between 0 and 7, more commonly known as CS0 through CS7, that can be used by quality of service (QoS) disciplines to differentiate and shape/police network traffic.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] COS operates only on 802.1Q VLAN Ethernet at the data link layer (layer 2), while other QoS mechanisms (such as DiffServ, also known as DSCP) operate at the IP network layer (layer 3) or use a local QoS tagging system that does not modify the actual packet, such as Cisco's "QoS-Group".
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] Network devices (i.e., routers, switches, etc.) can be configured to use existing COS values on incoming packets from other devices (trust mode) or can rewrite the COS value to something completely different.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] Most Internet Service Providers do not trust incoming QoS markings from their customers, so COS is generally limited to use within an organization's intranet.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] Service providers offering private-line WAN services will typically offer services that can utilize COS/QoS.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] As related to legacy telephone systems, COS is often used to define the permissions an extension will have on a PBX or Centrex.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] Certain groups of users may have a need for extended voicemail message retention, while another group may need the ability to forward calls to a cell phone, and still others have no need to make calls outside the office.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] Permissions for a group of extensions can be changed by modifying a COS variable applied to the entire group.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] COS is also used on trunks to define if they are full-duplex, incoming only, or outgoing only.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] The term can be used generically to refer to the classification of network traffic within network equipment based on packet inspection.
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] Cisco implements such classification through either access-lists or Network-Based Application Recognition (NBAR).
[src:qos-networking/class-of-service] NBAR works with the existing QoS system.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] DiffServ uses a 6-bit **differentiated services code point** (**DSCP**) in the 6-bit **differentiated services field** (**DS field**) in the IP header for packet classification purposes.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The DS field, together with the ECN field, replaces the outdated IPv4 TOS field.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Modern data networks carry many different types of services, including voice, video, streaming music, web pages and email.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Many of the proposed QoS mechanisms that allowed these services to co-exist were both complex and failed to scale to meet the demands of the public Internet.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] In December 1998, the IETF replaced the *TOS* and *IP precedence* fields in the IPv4 header with the *DS field*, which was later split to refer to only the top 6 bits with the *ECN field* in the bottom two bits.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] In the IPv6 header the *DS field* is part of the *Traffic Class* field where it occupies the 6 most significant bits.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] In the DS field, a range of eight values (class selectors) is used for backward compatibility with the former IPv4 *IP precedence* field.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Today, DiffServ has largely supplanted TOS and other layer-3 QoS mechanisms, such as integrated services (IntServ), as the primary architecture routers use to provide QoS.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] DiffServ is a *coarse-grained*, *class-based* mechanism for traffic management.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] In contrast, IntServ is a *fine-grained*, *flow-based* mechanism.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] DiffServ relies on a mechanism to *classify* and *mark* packets as belonging to a specific class.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] DiffServ-aware routers implement per-hop behaviors (PHBs), which define the packet-forwarding properties associated with a class of traffic.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Different PHBs may be defined to offer, for example, low-loss or low-latency service.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Rather than differentiating network traffic based on the requirements of an individual flow, DiffServ operates on the principle of traffic classification, placing each data packet into one of a limited number of traffic classes.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Each router on the network is then configured to differentiate traffic based on its class.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Each traffic class can be managed differently, ensuring preferential treatment for higher-priority traffic on the network.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The premise of DiffServ is that complicated functions such as packet classification and policing can be carried out at the edge of the network by edge routers.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Since no classification and policing is required in the core routers, functionality there can then be kept simple.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Core routers simply apply PHB treatment to packets based on their markings.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] PHB treatment is achieved by core routers using a combination of scheduling policy and queue management policy.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] A group of routers that implement common, administratively defined DiffServ policies are referred to as a *DiffServ domain*.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] While DiffServ does recommend a standardized set of traffic classes, the DiffServ architecture does not incorporate predetermined judgments of what types of traffic should be given priority treatment.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] DiffServ simply provides a framework to allow classification and differentiated treatment.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The standard traffic classes (discussed below) serve to simplify interoperability between different networks and different vendors' equipment.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Network traffic entering a DiffServ domain is subjected to classification and conditioning.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] A traffic classifier may inspect many different parameters in incoming packets, such as source address, destination address or traffic type and assign individual packets to a specific traffic class.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Traffic classifiers may honor any DiffServ markings in received packets or may elect to ignore or override those markings.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] For tight control over volumes and type of traffic in a given class, a network operator may choose not to honor markings at the ingress to the DiffServ domain.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Traffic in each class may be further conditioned by subjecting the traffic to rate limiters, traffic policers or shapers.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The per-hop behavior is determined by the DS and ECN fields in the IP header.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The DS field contains the 6-bit DSCP value.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN) occupies the least-significant 2 bits of the IPv4 TOS field and IPv6 traffic class (TC) field.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] In theory, a network could have up to 64 different traffic classes using the 64 available DSCP values.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The DiffServ RFCs recommend, but do not require, certain encodings.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] This gives a network operator great flexibility in defining traffic classes.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] A default forwarding (DF) PHB is the only required behavior.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Essentially, any traffic that does not meet the requirements of any of the other defined classes uses DF.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Typically, DF has best-effort forwarding characteristics.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The IETF defines Expedited Forwarding (EF) behavior in RFC 3246.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The EF PHB has the characteristics of low delay, low loss and low jitter.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] These characteristics are suitable for voice, video and other realtime services.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] EF traffic is often given strict priority queuing above all other traffic classes.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Because an overload of EF traffic will cause queuing delays and affect the jitter and delay tolerances within the class, admission control, traffic policing and other mechanisms may be applied to EF traffic.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The recommended DSCP for EF is 101110B (46 or 2EH).
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The IETF defines Voice Admit behavior in RFC 5865.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The Voice Admit PHB has identical characteristics to the Expedited Forwarding PHB.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] However, Voice Admit traffic is also admitted by the network using a Call Admission Control (CAC) procedure.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The recommended DSCP for voice admit is 101100B (44 or 2CH).
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The IETF defines the Assured Forwarding (AF) behavior in RFC 2597 and RFC 3260.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Assured forwarding allows the operator to provide assurance of delivery as long as the traffic does not exceed some subscribed rate.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Traffic that exceeds the subscription rate faces a higher probability of being dropped if congestion occurs.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The AF behavior group defines four separate AF classes, with all traffic within one class having the same priority.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Within each class, packets are given a drop precedence (high, medium or low, where higher precedence means *more* dropping).
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The combination of classes and drop precedence yields twelve separate DSCP encodings from AF11 through AF43 (see table).
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Some measure of priority and proportional fairness is defined between traffic in different classes.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Should congestion occur *between* classes, the traffic in the higher class is given priority.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Rather than using strict priority queuing, more balanced queue servicing algorithms such as fair queuing or weighted fair queuing are likely to be used.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] If congestion occurs *within* a class, the packets with the higher drop precedence are discarded first.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Re-marking a packet is sometimes used to increase its drop precedence if a stream's bandwidth exceeds a certain threshold.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] For example, a stream whose rate is above the Committed Information Rate (CIR) as defined in RFC 2697 causes the stream to be marked with a higher AF drop precedence.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] This allows the decision as to when to shape the stream to devices further downstream if they encounter congestion.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] To prevent issues associated with tail drop, more sophisticated drop selection algorithms such as random early detection are often used.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Prior to DiffServ, IPv4 networks could use the IP precedence field in the TOS byte of the IPv4 header to mark priority traffic.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The TOS octet and IP precedence were not widely used.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The IETF agreed to reuse the TOS octet as the DS field for DiffServ networks, later splitting it into the DS field and ECN field.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] In order to maintain backward compatibility with network devices that still use the Precedence field, DiffServ defines the *Class Selector* PHB.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The Class Selector code points are of the binary form 'xxx000'.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The first three bits are the former IP precedence bits.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Each IP precedence value can be mapped into a DiffServ class.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] IP precedence 0 maps to CS0, IP precedence 1 to CS1, and so on.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] If a packet is received from a non-DiffServ-aware router that used IP precedence markings, the DiffServ router can still understand the encoding as a Class Selector code point.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Specific recommendations for use of Class Selector code points are given in RFC 4594.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] RFC 4594 offers detailed and specific recommendations for the use and configuration of code points.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Other RFCs, such as RFC 8622, have updated these recommendations.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] A full list is provided in the IETF DSCP code point registry.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] sr+bs = single rate with burst size control (such as a token bucket).
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] Under DiffServ, all the policing and classifying are done at the boundaries between DiffServ domains.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] This means that in the core of the Internet, routers are unhindered by the complexities of collecting payment or enforcing agreements.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] That is, in contrast to IntServ, DiffServ requires no advance setup, no reservation, and no time-consuming end-to-end negotiation for each flow.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] The details of how individual routers deal with the DS field are configuration specific, therefore, it is difficult to predict end-to-end behavior.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] This is complicated further if a packet crosses two or more DiffServ domains before reaching its destination.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] From a commercial viewpoint, this means that it is impossible to sell different classes of end-to-end connectivity to end users, as one provider's Gold packet may be another's Bronze.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] DiffServ or any other IP-based QoS marking does not ensure the quality of the service or a specified service-level agreement (SLA).
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] By marking the packets, the sender indicates that it wants the packets to be treated as a specific service, but there is no guarantee this happens.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] It is up to all the service providers and their routers in the path to ensure that their policies will take care of the packets in an appropriate fashion.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] A Bandwidth Broker in the framework of DiffServ is an agent that has some knowledge of an organization's priorities and policies and allocates bandwidth with respect to those policies.
[src:qos-networking/differentiated-services] In order to achieve an end-to-end allocation of resources across separate domains, the Bandwidth Broker managing a domain will have to communicate with its adjacent peers, which allows end-to-end services to be constructed out of purely bilateral agreements.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] In computer networking, **integrated services** or **IntServ** is an architecture that specifies the elements to guarantee quality of service (QoS) on networks.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] IntServ can for example be used to allow video and sound to reach the receiver without interruption.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] IntServ specifies a fine-grained QoS system, which is often contrasted with DiffServ's coarse-grained control system.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] Under IntServ, every router in the system implements IntServ, and every application that requires some kind of QoS guarantee has to make an individual reservation.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] *Flow specs* describe what the reservation is for, while *RSVP* is the underlying mechanism to signal it across the network.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] TSPECs include token bucket algorithm parameters.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The idea is that there is a token bucket which slowly fills up with tokens, arriving at a constant rate.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] Every packet which is sent requires a token, and if there are no tokens, then it cannot be sent.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] Thus, the rate at which tokens arrive dictates the average rate of traffic flow, while the depth of the bucket dictates how 'bursty' the traffic is allowed to be.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] TSPECs typically just specify the token rate and the bucket depth.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] For example, a video with a refresh rate of 75 frames per second, with each frame taking 10 packets, might specify a token rate of 750 Hz, and a bucket depth of only 10.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The bucket depth would be sufficient to accommodate the 'burst' associated with sending an entire frame all at once.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] On the other hand, a conversation would need a lower token rate, but a much higher bucket depth.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] This is because there are often pauses in conversations, so they can make do with less tokens by not sending the gaps between words and sentences.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] However, this means the bucket depth needs to be increased to compensate for the traffic being burstier.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] RSpecs specify what requirements there are for the flow: it can be normal internet 'best effort', in which case no reservation is needed.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] This setting is likely to be used for webpages, FTP, and similar applications.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The 'Controlled Load' setting mirrors the performance of a lightly loaded network: there may be occasional glitches when two people access the same resource by chance, but generally both delay and drop rate are fairly constant at the desired rate.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] This setting is likely to be used by soft QoS applications.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The 'Guaranteed' setting gives an absolutely bounded service, where the delay is promised to never go above a desired amount, and packets never dropped, provided the traffic stays within spec.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) is described in RFC 2205.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] All machines on the network capable of sending QoS data send a PATH message every 30 seconds, which spreads out through the networks.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] Those who want to listen to them send a corresponding RESV (short for "Reserve") message which then traces the path backwards to the sender.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The RESV message contains the flow specs.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The routers between the sender and listener have to decide if they can support the reservation being requested, and, if they cannot, they send a reject message to let the listener know about it.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] Otherwise, once they accept the reservation they have to carry the traffic.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The routers then store the nature of the flow, and also police it.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] This is all done in soft state, so if nothing is heard for a certain length of time, then the reader will time out and the reservation will be cancelled.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] This solves the problem if either the sender or the receiver crash or are shut down incorrectly without first cancelling the reservation.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The individual routers may, at their option, police the traffic to check that it conforms to the flow specs.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] In order for IntServ to work, all routers along the traffic path must support it.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] Furthermore, many states must be stored in each router.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] As a result, IntServ works on a small-scale, but as the system scales up to larger networks or the Internet, it becomes resource intensive to track of all of the reservations.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] One way to solve the scalability problem is by using a multi-level approach, where per-microflow resource reservation (such as resource reservation for individual users) is done in the edge network, while in the core network resources are reserved for aggregate flows only.
[src:qos-networking/integrated-services] The routers that lie between these different levels must adjust the amount of aggregate bandwidth reserved from the core network so that the reservation requests for individual flows from the edge network can be better satisfied.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, quality of service refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is the ability to provide different priorities to different applications, users, or data flows, or to guarantee a certain level of performance to a data flow.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is particularly important for the transport of traffic with special requirements, including voice over IP and other audio networking techniques, professional video over IP, card-based payments, and real-time computing.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In the field of telephony, quality of service was defined by the ITU in 1994.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service comprises requirements on all the aspects of a connection, such as service response time, loss, signal-to-noise ratio, crosstalk, echo, interrupts, frequency response, loudness levels, and so on.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] A subset of telephony QoS is grade of service (GoS) requirements, which comprises aspects of a connection relating to capacity and coverage of a network, for example, guaranteed maximum blocking probability and outage probability.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, teletraffic engineering refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] For example, a required bit rate, delay, delay variation, packet loss or bit error rates may be guaranteed.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is important for real-time streaming multimedia applications such as voice over IP, multiplayer online games and IPTV, since these often require a fixed bit rate and are delay sensitive.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is especially important in networks where the capacity is a limited resource, for example, in cellular data communication.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] A network or protocol that supports QoS may agree on a traffic contract with the application software and reserve capacity in the network nodes, for example during a session establishment phase.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] During the session, it may monitor the achieved level of performance, for example, the data rate and delay, and dynamically control scheduling priorities in the network nodes.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] It may release the reserved capacity during a tear down phase.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] A best-effort network or service does not support quality of service.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication over a best-effort network by over-provisioning the capacity so that it is sufficient for the expected peak traffic load.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The resulting absence of network congestion reduces or eliminates the need for QoS mechanisms.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used as a quality measure, with many alternative definitions, rather than referring to the ability to reserve resources.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service sometimes refers to the level of quality of service, i.e. the guaranteed service quality.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] High QoS is often confused with a high level of performance, for example high bit rate, low latency and low bit error rate.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used in application layer services such as telephony and streaming video to describe a metric that reflects or predicts the subjectively experienced quality.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In this context, QoS is the acceptable cumulative effect on subscriber satisfaction of all imperfections affecting the service.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Other terms with similar meaning are the quality of experience (QoE), mean opinion score (MOS), perceptual speech quality measure (PSQM) and perceptual evaluation of video quality (PEVQ).
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] A number of attempts for layer 2 technologies that add QoS tags to the data have gained popularity in the past.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Examples are Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) (a technique between layer 2 and 3).
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Despite these network technologies remaining in use today, this kind of network lost attention after the advent of Ethernet networks.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Today, Ethernet is, by far, the most popular layer 2 technology.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Conventional Internet routers and network switches operate on a best-effort basis.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] This equipment is less expensive, less complex and faster and thus more popular than earlier, more complex technologies that provide QoS mechanisms.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Ethernet optionally uses 802.1p to signal the priority of a frame.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] There were four *type of service* bits and three *precedence* bits originally provided in each IP packet header, but they were not generally respected.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] These bits were later re-defined as Differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] With the advent of IPTV and IP telephony, QoS mechanisms are increasingly available to the end user.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In packet-switched networks, quality of service is affected by various factors, which can be divided into human and technical factors.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Human factors include: stability of service quality, availability of service, waiting times and user information.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Technical factors include: reliability, scalability, effectiveness, maintainability and network congestion.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Due to varying load from disparate users sharing the same network resources, the maximum throughput that can be provided to a certain data stream may be too low for real-time multimedia services.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The network may fail to deliver (*drop*) some packets due to network congestion.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The receiving application may ask for this information to be retransmitted, possibly resulting in congestive collapse or unacceptable delays in the overall transmission.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Sometimes packets are corrupted due to bit errors caused by noise and interference, especially in wireless communications and long copper wires.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The receiver has to detect this, and, just as if the packet was dropped, may ask for this information to be retransmitted.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] It might take a long time for each packet to reach its destination because it gets held up in long queues, or it takes a less direct route to avoid congestion.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In some cases, excessive latency can render an application such as VoIP or online gaming unusable.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Packets from the source will reach the destination with different delays.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] A packet's delay varies with its position in the queues of the routers along the path between source and destination, and this position can vary unpredictably.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Delay variation can be absorbed at the receiver, but in so doing increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] When a collection of related packets is routed through a network, different packets may take different routes, each resulting in a different delay.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The result is that the packets arrive in a different order than they were sent.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] This problem requires special additional protocols for rearranging out-of-order packets.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The reordering process requires additional buffering at the receiver, and, as with packet delay variation, increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] These types of service are called *inelastic*, meaning that they require a certain minimum bit rate and a certain maximum latency to function.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] By contrast, *elastic* applications can take advantage of however much or little bandwidth is available.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Bulk file transfer applications that rely on TCP are generally elastic.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Circuit-switched networks, especially those intended for voice transmission, such as ATM or GSM, have QoS in the core protocol; resources are reserved at each step on the network for the call as it is set up, and there is no need for additional procedures to achieve the required performance.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Shorter data units and built-in QoS were some of the unique selling points of ATM for applications such as video on demand.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication by generously over-provisioning a network so that capacity is based on peak traffic load estimates.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] This approach is simple for networks with predictable peak loads.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] This calculation may need to appreciate demanding applications that can compensate for variations in bandwidth and delay with large receive buffers, which is often possible, for example, in video streaming.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Over-provisioning can be of limited use in the face of transport protocols (such as TCP) that, over time, increase the amount of data placed on the network until all available bandwidth is consumed and packets are dropped.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Such greedy protocols tend to increase latency and packet loss for all users.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The amount of over-provisioning in interior links required to replace QoS depends on the number of users and their traffic demands.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] This limits the usability of over-provisioning.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Newer, more bandwidth-intensive applications and the addition of more users result in the loss of over-provisioned networks.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] This then requires a physical update of the relevant network links, which is an expensive process.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Thus, over-provisioning cannot be blindly assumed on the Internet.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Commercial VoIP services are often competitive with traditional telephone service in terms of call quality, even without QoS mechanisms in use on the user's connection to their ISP and the VoIP provider's connection to a different ISP.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Under high load conditions, however, VoIP may degrade to cell-phone quality or worse.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The mathematics of packet traffic indicates that the network requires just 60% more raw capacity under conservative assumptions.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Unlike single-owner networks, the Internet is a series of exchange points interconnecting private networks.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Hence the Internet's core is owned and managed by a number of different network service providers, not a single entity.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Its behavior is much more unpredictable.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] There are two principal approaches to QoS in modern packet-switched IP networks: a parameterized system based on an exchange of application requirements with the network, and a prioritized system where each packet identifies a desired service level to the network.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Early work used the integrated services (IntServ) philosophy of reserving network resources.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In this model, applications used RSVP to request and reserve resources through a network.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] While IntServ mechanisms do work, it was realized that in a broadband network typical of a larger service provider, Core routers would be required to accept, maintain, and tear down thousands or possibly tens of thousands of reservations.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] It was believed that this approach would not scale with the growth of the Internet, and in any event was antithetical to the end-to-end principle, the notion of designing networks so that core routers do little more than simply switch packets at the highest possible rates.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Under DiffServ, packets are marked either by the traffic sources themselves or by the edge devices where the traffic enters the network.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In response to these markings, routers and switches use various queuing strategies to tailor performance to requirements.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] At the IP layer, DSCP markings use the 6-bit DS field in the IP packet header.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] At the MAC layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q can be used to carry 3 bits of essentially the same information.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Routers and switches supporting DiffServ configure their network scheduler to use multiple queues for packets awaiting transmission from bandwidth-constrained (e.g., wide area) interfaces.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Router vendors provide different capabilities for configuring this behavior, including the number of queues supported, the relative priorities of queues, and the bandwidth reserved for each queue.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In practice, when a packet must be forwarded from an interface with queuing, packets requiring low jitter (e.g., VoIP or videoconferencing) are given priority over packets in other queues.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Typically, some bandwidth is allocated by default to network control packets (such as Internet Control Message Protocol and routing protocols), while best-effort traffic might simply be given whatever bandwidth is left over.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] At the medium access control (MAC) layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q and IEEE 802.1p can be used to distinguish between Ethernet frames and classify them.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Queueing theory models have been developed on performance analysis and QoS for MAC layer protocols.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Cisco IOS NetFlow and the Cisco Class Based QoS (CBQoS) Management Information Base (MIB) are marketed by Cisco Systems.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] One compelling example of the need for QoS on the Internet relates to congestive collapse.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The Internet relies on congestion avoidance protocols, primarily as built into Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), to reduce traffic under conditions that would otherwise lead to congestive collapse.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] QoS applications, such as VoIP and IPTV, require largely constant bitrates and low latency, therefore they cannot use TCP and cannot otherwise reduce their traffic rate to help prevent congestion.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Service-level agreements limit traffic that can be offered to the Internet and thereby enforce traffic shaping that can prevent it from becoming overloaded, and are hence an indispensable part of the Internet's ability to handle a mix of real-time and non-real-time traffic without collapse.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Several QoS mechanisms and schemes exist for IP networking.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] QoS capabilities are available in the following network technologies.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] End-to-end quality of service can require a method of coordinating resource allocation between one autonomous system and another.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for bandwidth reservation as a proposed standard in 1997.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] RSVP is an end-to-end bandwidth reservation and admission control protocol.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] RSVP was not widely adopted due to scalability limitations.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The more scalable traffic engineering version, RSVP-TE, is used in many networks to establish traffic-engineered Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) label-switched paths.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The IETF also defined Next Steps in Signaling (NSIS) with QoS signalling as a target.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] NSIS is a development and simplification of RSVP.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Research consortia such as "end-to-end quality of service support over heterogeneous networks" (EuQoS, from 2004 through 2007) and fora such as the IPsphere Forum developed more mechanisms for handshaking QoS invocation from one domain to the next.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] IPsphere defined the Service Structuring Stratum (SSS) signaling bus in order to establish, invoke and (attempt to) assure network services.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] EuQoS conducted experiments to integrate Session Initiation Protocol, Next Steps in Signaling and IPsphere's SSS with an estimated cost of about 15.6 million Euro and published a book.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] A research project Multi Service Access Everywhere (MUSE) defined another QoS concept in a first phase from January 2004 through February 2006, and a second phase from January 2006 through 2007.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Another research project named PlaNetS was proposed for European funding circa 2005.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] A broader European project called "Architecture and design for the future Internet" known as 4WARD had a budget estimated at 23.4 million Euro and was funded from January 2008 through June 2010.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] It included a "Quality of Service Theme" and published a book.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Another European project, called WIDENS (Wireless Deployable Network System), proposed a bandwidth reservation approach for mobile wireless multirate adhoc networks.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Strong cryptography network protocols such as Secure Sockets Layer, I2P, and virtual private networks obscure the data transferred using them.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] As all electronic commerce on the Internet requires the use of such strong cryptography protocols, unilaterally downgrading the performance of encrypted traffic creates an unacceptable hazard for customers.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Yet, encrypted traffic is otherwise unable to undergo deep packet inspection for QoS.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Protocols like ICA and RDP may encapsulate other traffic (e.g. printing, video streaming) with varying requirements that can make optimization difficult.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The Internet2 project found, in 2001, that the QoS protocols were probably not deployable inside its Abilene Network with equipment available at that time.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The group predicted that "logistical, financial, and organizational barriers will block the way toward any bandwidth guarantees" by protocol modifications aimed at QoS.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] They believed that the economics would encourage network providers to deliberately erode the quality of best effort traffic as a way to push customers to higher-priced QoS services.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Instead, they proposed over-provisioning of capacity as more cost-effective at the time.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The Abilene network study was the basis for the testimony of Gary Bachula to the US Senate Commerce Committee's hearing on Network Neutrality in early 2006.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] He expressed the opinion that adding more bandwidth was more effective than any of the various schemes for accomplishing QoS they examined.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Bachula's testimony has been cited by proponents of a law banning quality of service as proof that no legitimate purpose is served by such an offering.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] This argument is dependent on the assumption that over-provisioning isn't a form of QoS and that it is always possible.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Cost and other factors affect the ability of carriers to build and maintain permanently over-provisioned networks.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Mobile cellular service providers may offer mobile QoS to customers just as the wired public switched telephone network service providers and Internet service providers may offer QoS.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] QoS mechanisms are always provided for circuit switched services, and are essential for inelastic services, for example streaming multimedia.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Mobility adds complications to QoS mechanisms.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] A phone call or other session may be interrupted after a handover if the new base station is overloaded.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Unpredictable handovers make it impossible to give an absolute QoS guarantee during the session initiation phase.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service in the field of telephony was first defined in 1994 in ITU-T Recommendation E.800.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] This definition is very broad, listing 6 primary components: Support, Operability, Accessibility, Retainability, Integrity and Security.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] In 1998 the ITU published a document discussing QoS in the field of data networking.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] X.641 offers a means of developing or enhancing standards related to QoS and provides concepts and terminology that should assist in maintaining the consistency of related standards.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] Some QoS-related IETF Request for Comments (RFC)s are *Baker, Fred; Black, David L.; Nichols, Kathleen; Blake, Steven L.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] (December 1998), *Definition of the Differentiated services Field (DS Field) in the IPv4 and IPv6 Headers*, doi:10.17487/RFC2474, RFC 2474*, and *Braden, Robert T.; Zhang, Lixia; Berson, Steven; Herzog, Shai; Jamin, Sugih (September 1997), Braden, R.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] (ed.), *Resource ReSerVation Protocol (RSVP)*, doi:10.17487/RFC2205, RFC 2205*; both these are discussed above.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The IETF has also published two RFCs giving background on QoS: *Huston, Geoff (November 2000), *Next Steps for the IP QoS Architecture*, doi:10.17487/RFC2990, RFC 2990*, and *Floyd, S.; Kempf, J.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] (ed.), *IAB Concerns Regarding Congestion Control for Voice Traffic in the Internet*, doi:10.17487/RFC3714, RFC 3714*.
[src:qos-networking/quality-of-service] The document tries to identify applications commonly run over an IP network, groups them into traffic classes, studies the treatment required by these classes from the network, and suggests which of the QoS mechanisms commonly available in routers can be used to implement those treatments.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] The **type of service** (**ToS**) field is the second byte of the IPv4 header.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] It has had various purposes over the years, and has been defined in different ways by five RFCs.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Before the redefinition, the ToS field could specify a datagram's priority and request a route for low-latency, high-throughput, or highly-reliable service.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Based on these ToS values, a packet would be placed in a prioritized outgoing queue or take a route with appropriate latency, throughput, or reliability.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] In practice, the ToS field never saw widespread use outside of the US Department of Defense networks.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] However, a great deal of experimental, research, and deployment work has focused on how to make use of these eight bits, resulting in the current DS field definition.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] The modern redefinition of the ToS field (as well as the *Traffic Class* field in IPv6 packets) splits this byte into a 6-bit Differentiated Services (DS) field and a 2-bit Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN) field.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] While Differentiated Services is somewhat backwards compatible with ToS, ECN is not.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] The Type of Service field in the IP header was originally defined in RFC 791, and has been interpreted for *IP Precedence* and *ToS* ever since.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] The definition was largely derived from a US DoD Specification JANAP-128, which defines message multilevel precedence and preemption.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] It defined a mechanism for assigning a precedence to each IP packet, as well as a mechanism to request specific treatment such as high throughput, high reliability, or low latency, etc.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] In the RFC 1349 update, the Monetary Cost bit is introduced (this bit was previously marked "Reserved for Future Use").
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Section 2.4 of RFC 1583 (OSPFv2) introduces a ToS-aware routing method.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] In practice, only the IP Precedence part of the field was ever used outside US DoD networks: the higher the value of the IP Precedence field, the higher the priority of the IP packet.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Some US DoD networks did use the delay bit for route selection between oceanic cable paths and Satellite Communication (SATCOM) paths when both paths existed.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] IPv6 has never had an IPv4-like "traditional" ToS field, partially because the authors were aware of DiffServ efforts at its drafting (RFC 2460 Section 7).
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] In RFC 2474, the definition of this entire field was changed.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] It is now called the "DS" (Differentiated Services, "DiffServ") field, and the upper 6 bits contain a value called the "DSCP" (Differentiated Services Code Point).
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] The upper 3 bits of DS maintain compatibility with IP Precedence.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Since RFC 3168, the remaining two bits (the two least significant bits) are used for Explicit Congestion Notification.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] RFC 8622 added lower-effort (LE) DS for traffic that may be pre-empted by other traffic (best-effort traffic).
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] It is intended for background traffic of low precedence, such as bulk data transfers with low priority in time.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Precedence was a 3 bit field which treats high priority packets as more important than other packets.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] If a router is congested and needs to discard some packets, it will discard packets having the lowest priority first.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Although the precedence field was part of IP version 4, it was never used.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] RFC 1349 introduced an additional "low-cost" field.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] The naming here follows the convention of Unix operating systems.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] RFC 1349 and RFC 1060 only show examples of one bit used at a time for application-default values, although RFC 791 mentions that at most two of the three indications it has should be set nominally.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Because the last three bits went through many definitions prior to RFC 2474 (see below), documentation and implementations may be confusing and contradictory.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] RFC 2474 (which was released in December 1998) reserved the first six bits of the DS (or IPv4 ToS) field for the Differentiated Services Code Point (DSCP), and RFC 3168 reserved the last two bits for Explicit Congestion Notification.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Note: In the above table, ToS is shown in decimal format.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] However, many routers express ToS in hex format.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Let's start with an IP precedence of 1, or `001` in binary.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] The entire ToS field would then be `001 00000`, assuming that the unused 5 bits are zero.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] The DSCP can be interpreted by resegmenting to `001000 00`, where `001000` = 8 is the DSCP value, corresponding to CS1.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Although not frequently used, IP ToS definitions are widely found in `netinet/ip.h` of Unix-like or Unix operating systems as `IPTOS_FIELDNAME` macros.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] The "lowcost" field is commented out in OpenBSD due to its newer use for indicating ECN support.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] Remnants of the old RFC 1349 terminology can be found in Transmission 2.93 as well as other tools that support setting this field.
[src:qos-networking/type-of-service] An old Apache module, "mod_iptos", once packaged in Ubuntu, notes that a way to use multiple RFC 1349 option bits together emerged after some point.
